<DOC><DOCNO> AP890921-0254 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-09-21-89 1256EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-UAL     09-21 0203</FIRST><SECOND>PM-UAL,0213</SECOND><HEAD>Tender Offer for UAL To Begin Today</HEAD><DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   The total cost of an employee-management group'sleveraged buyout of UAL Corp. would be $9.45 billion, according to amerger agreement filed with the Securities and Exchange Commission.   The $300-a-share tender offer for the parent company of UnitedAirlines was to begin today.   According to the agreement filed with the SEC, the buyout groupwill require $6.8 billion to purchase UAL's 22.65 million fullydiluted shares. It said the group may refinance $950 million inexisting UAL debt, which would leave $512 million in long-term debtand $411 million in capital leases outstanding.   In addition, there are fees and a $1.3 billion credit facilityfor working capital included in the total buyout cost.   In addition to management personnel and United pilots, the buyoutgroup includes British Airways PLC as a minority partner.   The group plans to finance the transaction with $750 million fromBritish Airways; $200 million in voluntary pension contributionsfrom the pilots; $1.3 billion from UAL cash reserves and $7.2billion in bank loans.   The buyout would give UAL nonmanagement employees 75 percentownership.   Around midday on the New York Stock Exchange, UAL was up $2.12{to $287.12{.</TEXT></DOC>